WEBVTT

00:04.874 --> 00:07.442
♪

00:16.146 --> 00:18.931
[Clay sighs]

00:18.975 --> 00:21.195
I'd be lying if I said
this one wasn't messing

00:21.238 --> 00:22.457
with my head a little bit.

00:22.500 --> 00:24.633
Well, I almost told
the cake-eaters

00:24.676 --> 00:27.157
where they could shove this
particular good idea.

00:31.422 --> 00:33.990
Can't imagine how this feels
for you.

00:37.037 --> 00:39.517
What makes you think
this idea's so bad?

00:45.262 --> 00:46.524
History.

00:48.787 --> 00:50.485
[softly]:
Emma...

00:50.528 --> 00:53.140
♪ Emma, Emma, Bo-bemma

00:53.183 --> 00:54.576
[imitating airplane]

00:54.619 --> 00:55.968
Hey, today's the day,
Emma-phant.

00:56.012 --> 00:57.318
You're gonna crawl.
I can feel it.

00:57.361 --> 00:59.102
[helicopter flying overhead]

00:59.146 --> 01:00.625
Come on, you were doing that
"rev your motor" thing

01:00.669 --> 01:02.366
all weekend.
You've got all the pieces,

01:02.410 --> 01:05.152
just... just put 'em together.

01:05.195 --> 01:08.242
Okay. You know what you need
is incentive.

01:08.285 --> 01:09.460
Okay?

01:09.504 --> 01:11.158
Ooh... look at that.

01:11.201 --> 01:13.029
You're gonna go get it.

01:13.073 --> 01:15.205
Come on, go get it.

01:15.249 --> 01:17.033
ALANA:
Jason! She's your daughter,

01:17.077 --> 01:20.167
she's not a dog to play fetch
with.

01:20.210 --> 01:23.518
You're right.
A dog obeys commands.

01:23.561 --> 01:25.085
I don't get it.
Liz and Reed's baby

01:25.128 --> 01:26.216
was crawling at this age.

01:26.260 --> 01:28.131
Well, life isn't a competition.

01:28.175 --> 01:30.133
[baby voice]:
Don't listen to your mother.

01:30.177 --> 01:32.831
Oh, no, no, no.

01:32.875 --> 01:34.964
Maybe I should give up on her
and focus on the next one?

01:35.007 --> 01:36.313
ALANA:
"Next one"?

01:36.357 --> 01:38.010
Not until this one's
potty trained--

01:38.054 --> 01:40.448
unless you plan on pulling
double diaper duty with me.

01:40.491 --> 01:43.277
Yeah, not what I meant when
I requested more dirty talk.

01:43.320 --> 01:45.279
[chuckles]

01:46.671 --> 01:48.717
You should check your clock,
Spielberg,

01:48.760 --> 01:50.197
you're gonna be late for work.

01:50.240 --> 01:52.373
Pick me up.
Come on. Come on, Emma.

01:52.416 --> 01:54.288
[sighs]

01:54.331 --> 01:56.203
Hey, record everything.

01:56.246 --> 01:57.552
-Yeah.
-I love you.

02:02.339 --> 02:03.993
-Hey.
-[Emma cooing]

02:04.036 --> 02:05.473
Love you, buddy.

02:05.516 --> 02:06.735
You're gonna crawl.

02:06.778 --> 02:08.476
Okay? You can do it.

02:08.519 --> 02:10.869
Ooh, you can do it.

02:12.219 --> 02:14.569
♪

02:28.191 --> 02:31.412
Guess you've got the long-view.

02:31.455 --> 02:32.674
You've been in the Navy

02:32.717 --> 02:34.066
since I was in kindergarten.

02:34.110 --> 02:35.590
Kindergarten?

02:35.633 --> 02:37.896
Thought you spent your childhood
spreading the word

02:37.940 --> 02:40.464
with your grandparents.

02:42.597 --> 02:44.468
My mom dumped me with them
the next summer.

02:44.512 --> 02:47.036
♪

02:49.865 --> 02:51.649
You, uh...

02:51.693 --> 02:52.955
you bring it on board with you

02:52.998 --> 02:54.261
or did you let the ground crew
stow it?

03:00.615 --> 03:03.400
[Jason sighs]

03:03.444 --> 03:05.924
I haven't let it out of
my sight.

03:05.968 --> 03:07.970
Can I see it?

03:08.013 --> 03:10.015
♪

03:19.851 --> 03:21.113
Hey, kiddo.

03:21.157 --> 03:22.680
How was the trip in?

03:22.724 --> 03:25.030
-[places suitcase down]
-It was fine.

03:25.074 --> 03:27.119
The long flight didn't wear you
out did it?

03:27.163 --> 03:28.773
I'm good.

03:28.817 --> 03:30.253
Got a pretty big week planned.

03:30.297 --> 03:32.299
Got a ceremony today,
a little party, right?

03:32.342 --> 03:33.822
Hey.

03:33.865 --> 03:36.825
The "reel" fun starts tomorrow!

03:36.868 --> 03:38.653
Check it out.
[laughs]

03:38.696 --> 03:40.350
The "reel" fun!

03:42.222 --> 03:43.832
Used to love that joke when you
were little.

03:43.875 --> 03:45.660
You remember when I took you
fishing in the Chesapeake

03:45.703 --> 03:47.662
to catch mackerel?

03:47.705 --> 03:49.664
You used to hate baiting
your own hook, right?

03:49.707 --> 03:51.840
The sand eel, they used to
freak you out a little bit.

03:51.883 --> 03:53.842
Doesn't bother me anymore.

03:53.885 --> 03:56.497
Grammy and Poppa taught me how
to bait in the Gulf of Guinea.

03:57.498 --> 04:00.065
Taught me a lot of things.

04:01.066 --> 04:04.809
Good. I'm glad.

04:04.853 --> 04:06.507
[inhales, exhales]

04:06.550 --> 04:09.379
You know what else
I'm glad about?

04:09.423 --> 04:11.468
I'm glad they brought you here
to help you celebrate

04:11.512 --> 04:12.730
your old man's retirement.

04:12.774 --> 04:15.994
That means a lot to me, son.

04:16.038 --> 04:17.648
And you know what else?

04:17.692 --> 04:19.868
I get to spend the week
with you-- mm!--

04:19.911 --> 04:21.870
without worrying about getting
called into work!

04:21.913 --> 04:24.525
[Ash laughs]

04:24.568 --> 04:25.874
Can't wait.

04:28.180 --> 04:30.748
[indistinct radio chatter]

04:33.882 --> 04:35.927
♪

04:40.062 --> 04:42.891
[bell ringing]

04:42.934 --> 04:45.328
[indistinct chatter]

04:47.504 --> 04:48.679
[footsteps approaching]

04:48.723 --> 04:50.246
MRS. HILL:
Good morning!

04:50.290 --> 04:54.337
[indistinct chatter continues]

04:54.381 --> 04:58.123
Weekend's over, everyone,
so let's focus.

04:58.167 --> 04:59.995
-[chatter stops]
-Thank you.

05:00.038 --> 05:01.388
I hope you all've made progress

05:01.431 --> 05:03.694
on your research project
proposals.

05:05.522 --> 05:07.916
Let's find out who our first

05:07.959 --> 05:11.006
three presentations
will come from tomorrow.

05:13.313 --> 05:15.445
[jar rattling]

05:17.926 --> 05:19.101
Melanie Rudolph.

05:21.408 --> 05:22.583
Matt Peters.

05:22.626 --> 05:24.933
[Matt groans]

05:24.976 --> 05:26.717
And...

05:26.761 --> 05:28.980
[paper rustling]

05:29.024 --> 05:30.330
Lisa Davis.

05:30.373 --> 05:32.114
[Lisa groans]

05:32.157 --> 05:35.160
Please take out your homework
from last week, pass it forward,

05:35.204 --> 05:37.337
and turn to chapter ten.

05:37.380 --> 05:39.339
♪

05:45.127 --> 05:47.085
Sonny, stop, all right? Hey!

05:47.129 --> 05:48.739
We've got a long day
ahead of us.

05:48.783 --> 05:51.002
Just sit down, and save
your energy for later, okay?

05:51.046 --> 05:52.264
[Sonny sighs]

05:52.308 --> 05:54.615
Come on.

05:54.658 --> 05:57.531
[sighing]:
Right. Right.

05:57.574 --> 05:59.620
["All I Want"
by All Systems Go! playing]

06:06.366 --> 06:08.150
[music playing on headphones]

06:08.193 --> 06:11.153
HANNAH: Took you less than three
weeks to stop knocking first.

06:11.196 --> 06:12.981
Manners are for strangers
and roommates.

06:13.024 --> 06:14.374
[grunts]

06:14.417 --> 06:15.810
Not my fault Hannah Oliver
somehow gets

06:15.853 --> 06:17.942
a single as a freshman.

06:17.986 --> 06:20.336
Okay, what if I was
in here with a guy?

06:20.380 --> 06:22.164
Then the door would be locked.

06:22.207 --> 06:25.036
Unless you're some sort of
kinky voyeur.

06:25.080 --> 06:27.691
That would make me an
exhibition-- never mind.

06:27.735 --> 06:29.824
How was rehearsal?

06:29.867 --> 06:32.000
Wet Burrito ready for their
big debut Friday?

06:32.043 --> 06:33.741
[closes door]

06:33.784 --> 06:36.178
Wet Burrito has made it
to its inevitable resting place:

06:36.221 --> 06:38.180
the toilet.

06:38.223 --> 06:39.747
HANNAH:
What's that mean?

06:39.790 --> 06:42.706
-I'm not in the band anymore.
-You quit?

06:44.360 --> 06:46.449
They kicked you out?

06:46.493 --> 06:47.755
Maybe a little of both.

06:49.060 --> 06:50.497
[sighs]

06:50.540 --> 06:52.455
Comes a time in every man's life
when he realizes

06:52.499 --> 06:54.109
music isn't his thing,

06:54.152 --> 06:55.806
and he moves on.

06:55.850 --> 06:57.417
So what's next?

06:57.460 --> 06:59.201
The last three months
you tried the band,

06:59.244 --> 07:00.550
and night club promoting,

07:00.594 --> 07:01.986
and even jujitsu for a while.

07:02.030 --> 07:03.684
Hmm...

07:03.727 --> 07:06.469
It's too bad Sensei Stu
was running a pyramid scheme.

07:06.513 --> 07:08.210
I looked tight in my gi.

07:08.253 --> 07:09.951
You know, you could
always go back to the ranch.

07:09.994 --> 07:12.083
I'm sure Emmet would love
to have you.

07:12.127 --> 07:15.696
[both laughing]

07:15.739 --> 07:17.698
Or, you spend so much time
on campus,

07:17.741 --> 07:20.570
you might as well enroll.

07:25.270 --> 07:26.968
High school was boring enough.

07:27.011 --> 07:28.273
Well, there are a lot more
options here

07:28.317 --> 07:30.058
than in high school.

07:30.101 --> 07:32.321
Might help you find whatever
it is you're looking for.

07:32.364 --> 07:34.366
♪

07:40.634 --> 07:43.201
[indistinct radio chatter]

07:55.997 --> 08:00.044
♪

08:09.227 --> 08:11.926
[distant siren blaring]

08:11.969 --> 08:14.798
-[door buzzing]
-[indistinct chatter]

08:14.842 --> 08:17.497
-Really appreciate this, Phil.
-No problem, Captain Perry.

08:17.540 --> 08:19.411
Make sure you try to keep one
in the park next time

08:19.455 --> 08:20.500
we play your station.

08:20.543 --> 08:23.198
[laughing]:
Can't make any promises.

08:30.205 --> 08:32.163
Breathalyzer you blew
when they picked you up

08:32.207 --> 08:35.471
means you're probably
dehydrated.

08:35.515 --> 08:37.604
On your feet, Raymond.

08:39.736 --> 08:42.260
♪

08:54.664 --> 08:57.493
[indistinct radio chatter]

08:57.537 --> 09:00.017
♪

09:13.248 --> 09:16.033
♪

09:28.132 --> 09:29.612
Worried about him.

09:29.656 --> 09:31.614
He's fine.

09:31.658 --> 09:33.398
North Korea proved it.

09:33.442 --> 09:34.617
CLAY:
Not what I mean.

09:34.661 --> 09:36.097
Leave him be, all right?

09:36.140 --> 09:37.359
He needs anything,
he'll let us know.

09:37.402 --> 09:40.710
♪

09:54.419 --> 09:56.552
Still waiting on a "thank you."

09:56.596 --> 09:58.902
For what?
I didn't do anything.

09:58.946 --> 10:02.471
Underage consumption of alcohol
says otherwise.

10:02.514 --> 10:04.212
Blood on your hands

10:04.255 --> 10:07.345
might also convince a judge
to agree with disorderly conduct

10:07.389 --> 10:09.347
and criminal mischief.

10:09.391 --> 10:11.611
You need to be better than this.

10:15.310 --> 10:17.573
You wanna tell me what you got
yourself into

10:17.617 --> 10:21.011
that I had to pull a favor
to get you out of?

10:21.055 --> 10:22.186
It was nothing.

10:22.230 --> 10:24.406
Nothing?

10:24.449 --> 10:26.103
Your favorite pastime!

10:26.147 --> 10:28.584
Maybe if you were doing
something--

10:28.628 --> 10:31.108
a job, school--

10:31.152 --> 10:34.111
maybe you wouldn't have so much
time for nothing.

10:34.155 --> 10:39.029
Look, I've heard this tired
old speech a thousand times.

10:39.073 --> 10:41.205
Don't you have a cat to pull out
of a tree?

10:43.381 --> 10:46.471
Cat's worth saving. But you?

10:46.515 --> 10:50.737
Stay on this path to nowhere,
you walk it alone.

10:50.780 --> 10:53.478
This is the last time
I stand between you

10:53.522 --> 10:55.480
and the criminal record
you seem determined

10:55.524 --> 10:57.613
to create for yourself.

11:00.137 --> 11:01.356
Okay.

11:01.399 --> 11:03.924
"Okay"?

11:06.535 --> 11:08.058
That's all you have to say?

11:10.365 --> 11:12.062
Thanks, Pop.

11:20.157 --> 11:23.291
"The United States did not enter
World War II

11:23.334 --> 11:26.468
"until after December 7, 1941,

11:26.511 --> 11:27.774
"a day that will live in infamy.

11:27.817 --> 11:29.210
"On that day, Japanese forces

11:29.253 --> 11:30.733
attacked Pearl Harbor
in the then-territory..."

11:30.777 --> 11:31.952
RONNIE:
I'm hungry.

11:31.995 --> 11:34.128
I'm doing homework.

11:34.171 --> 11:35.738
Mom will be home soon.

11:35.782 --> 11:38.349
No, she won't.
She's out with her friend Andre.

11:38.393 --> 11:39.611
She said she'll be back late.

11:39.655 --> 11:40.830
What?

11:40.874 --> 11:42.353
Why didn't you tell me?

11:42.397 --> 11:44.529
'Cause I forgot till now.

11:44.573 --> 11:46.357
Did she leave anything for me
to heat up?

11:46.401 --> 11:48.925
Nope. She said you're
in charge of figuring it out.

11:48.969 --> 11:51.188
Damn it, Ronnie, wish I'd known!

11:51.232 --> 11:53.974
-I'm hungry, Lisa.
-Okay, just give me a sec,

11:54.017 --> 11:55.453
I need to finish this one...
-Now!

11:55.497 --> 11:57.542
One sec!

11:57.586 --> 11:59.719
-Ow, I'm telling!
-Damn it, Ronnie!

11:59.762 --> 12:03.635
It's not my fault!
I told you I was hungry!

12:05.246 --> 12:06.551
[sighs]

12:08.771 --> 12:11.034
Come on.

12:11.078 --> 12:14.037
Let's go get cleaned up
and then I'll start dinner.

12:20.914 --> 12:25.527
-[indistinct chatter]
-[music playing]

12:25.570 --> 12:27.703
I'm disappointed you
didn't get to make a speech.

12:27.747 --> 12:30.010
Well, doesn't work like that.

12:30.053 --> 12:31.707
Besides, I don't have to be
the center of attention

12:31.751 --> 12:32.882
all the time.

12:32.926 --> 12:34.666
[laughs]

12:34.710 --> 12:36.843
Stories you could have told.

12:36.886 --> 12:38.888
You know your old man blew up
Noriega's boat?

12:38.932 --> 12:41.717
Leave him alone. He doesn't
even know who Noriega is.

12:41.761 --> 12:43.763
You blew up a boat?

12:43.806 --> 12:45.852
Well, it was more like a yacht.

12:45.895 --> 12:48.245
Drug money gets all
the best toys, right?

12:48.289 --> 12:50.030
[laughing]

12:50.073 --> 12:52.206
How far down did you
have to dive?

12:54.861 --> 12:57.994
You know, it was like
30 or 40 feet.

12:58.038 --> 13:00.518
But we survived.

13:00.562 --> 13:03.565
Four men on the airfield that
day weren't quite as lucky.

13:03.608 --> 13:05.610
-They died?
-They sure did.

13:05.654 --> 13:08.526
In service to their country
and there's no greater honor.

13:10.485 --> 13:12.313
[bartender opens bottle]

13:13.836 --> 13:16.752
Did you ever almost...?

13:18.406 --> 13:21.539
The world calmed down on
the back nine of my career, son.

13:21.583 --> 13:25.456
I spent most of my time
out of the line of fire.

13:25.500 --> 13:29.243
You were on three
active operations, Spenser.

13:29.286 --> 13:30.679
More than any other frogman
I know.

13:32.724 --> 13:35.684
Your dad might go down as
a legend with a résumé like his.

13:35.727 --> 13:38.165
If that means my boy
gets to grows up on a planet

13:38.208 --> 13:39.644
that gives peace
a half a chance,

13:39.688 --> 13:41.124
then I will humbly

13:41.168 --> 13:42.734
wear that legend title.

13:42.778 --> 13:44.693
[laughs]

13:44.736 --> 13:47.217
Get some quarters, come on.

13:48.175 --> 13:49.567
Get ready to roll.

13:49.611 --> 13:51.047
We're four in a row
with no mistakes.

13:51.091 --> 13:52.788
Five'll make me proud.

13:52.832 --> 13:55.051
Shouldn't be a problem
with a team this slick.

13:55.095 --> 13:57.837
Feels like we're being graded
on a curve.

13:57.880 --> 13:59.926
There a problem, Hayes?

13:59.969 --> 14:02.232
Just hard to know how slick
we really are

14:02.276 --> 14:03.538
when we're just playing pretend.

14:03.581 --> 14:05.018
You're tired of clearing houses?

14:05.061 --> 14:06.889
No, we're hitting dingers in BP.

14:06.933 --> 14:10.327
True test of skill only happens
when the game's on the line.

14:12.939 --> 14:14.157
Bolt cutters up!

14:14.201 --> 14:16.246
♪

14:24.907 --> 14:26.691
Cut there.

14:26.735 --> 14:29.999
Might take some time, but
eventually you'll get an at bat.

14:30.826 --> 14:32.175
Open!

14:32.219 --> 14:34.699
♪

14:38.399 --> 14:40.357
"Eventually."

14:48.235 --> 14:49.932
30 minutes out.

14:49.976 --> 14:51.542
[grunting]:
Oh, man,

14:51.586 --> 14:53.327
it's been like ten years
since I've been here.

14:53.370 --> 14:55.068
-Ten years?
-Yeah.

14:55.111 --> 14:58.158
Yeah, probably same for me.

14:58.201 --> 14:59.855
Yeah, me, too.

14:59.899 --> 15:03.337
I haven't been here since before
Green Team.

15:03.380 --> 15:04.773
I've never been.

15:04.816 --> 15:06.644
♪

15:08.908 --> 15:11.301
RAY:
Chicken was delicious, Mom.

15:11.345 --> 15:12.999
Thank you.

15:13.042 --> 15:15.958
-You want some more?
-No.

15:16.002 --> 15:17.525
Good.

15:17.568 --> 15:21.224
If you're full,
that means you're happy.

15:21.268 --> 15:23.052
Which means we can talk about
what happened

15:23.096 --> 15:25.533
without you making a scene,
right?

15:25.576 --> 15:27.230
Talk about what?

15:27.274 --> 15:29.537
I didn't steal anything
and I didn't hurt anybody.

15:29.580 --> 15:31.539
That's a low bar.

15:31.582 --> 15:34.542
You used to have such focus,
such discipline.

15:34.585 --> 15:36.631
You know, you... you had plans.

15:36.674 --> 15:38.241
Yeah, and then Dad moved us here
from Jersey,

15:38.285 --> 15:41.244
and some punk from Veritas
broke my leg on the mat

15:41.288 --> 15:43.507
and then all the scholarships
went away.

15:43.551 --> 15:45.422
That was two years ago.
Time to find a new excuse.

15:45.466 --> 15:47.598
Jamal.

15:48.860 --> 15:50.036
DIANE:
Uh-uh.

15:50.079 --> 15:51.472
Wipe that look off your face.

15:51.515 --> 15:53.865
Your father has a point.

15:53.909 --> 15:57.043
Wrestling was a means to college
for you,

15:57.086 --> 15:59.132
not an end in itself.

15:59.175 --> 16:01.830
You were a good student.

16:01.873 --> 16:04.093
School is still an option.

16:04.137 --> 16:05.834
Maybe.

16:05.877 --> 16:08.358
But it isn't cheap,
and I don't want to waste money

16:08.402 --> 16:11.361
if I don't know what I want
to study.

16:11.405 --> 16:13.973
Whose money?
You don't have a job.

16:14.016 --> 16:16.236
Yeah, but if Mom's offering,
yours.

16:16.279 --> 16:18.499
I'm being fiscally responsible
on your behalf.

16:18.542 --> 16:21.415
[laughing]

16:21.458 --> 16:24.070
"Responsible"?

16:24.113 --> 16:25.549
Out of your mouth?

16:25.593 --> 16:27.160
You wanna learn some
responsibility,

16:27.203 --> 16:28.683
we can arrange that.

16:28.726 --> 16:32.426
Your own roof, your own food,
your own dime.

16:32.469 --> 16:34.732
We are not kicking our son
out of the house.

16:34.776 --> 16:36.169
Your pampering's great
motivation for him

16:36.212 --> 16:37.431
to straighten out.

16:37.474 --> 16:38.998
[Diane sighs]

16:39.041 --> 16:40.521
Who's ready for dessert?

16:40.564 --> 16:42.044
Wrap mine up to go.

16:42.088 --> 16:43.567
I'll eat at the station.

16:43.611 --> 16:45.091
I thought your
rotation was over.

16:45.134 --> 16:50.009
It was, until I traded shifts
to go save our son's ass.

16:51.097 --> 16:53.099
He gets all worked up
over nothing.

16:54.230 --> 16:57.059
I'm fine, Mom.

16:57.103 --> 16:58.365
You're not, Ray.

16:58.408 --> 17:01.846
We're both worried about you.

17:01.890 --> 17:06.938
And you may not like
your father's words or tone,

17:06.982 --> 17:09.332
but what he's saying
isn't wrong.

17:09.376 --> 17:11.769
♪

17:11.813 --> 17:13.554
[knock at door]

17:17.297 --> 17:19.690
Hi, Miss Gladys.
Do you need me to come down

17:19.734 --> 17:20.996
and change a light bulb?

17:21.040 --> 17:22.345
No, no, I'm all good, honey.

17:22.389 --> 17:24.173
Came up to check on you girls.

17:24.217 --> 17:26.349
Thought I heard a
little trouble earlier...

17:26.393 --> 17:30.005
Oh, that was just Ronnie belting
"Lady Marmalade."

17:30.049 --> 17:32.094
-[Gladys chuckling]
-Kid thinks she's
Christina Aguilera.

17:32.138 --> 17:33.487
Sorry to disturb you.

17:33.530 --> 17:35.054
I'll make sure she keeps it
down.

17:35.097 --> 17:36.490
Oh, no apology necessary.

17:36.533 --> 17:41.016
Glad it was just
the exuberance of youth.

17:41.060 --> 17:43.192
What's that?

17:43.236 --> 17:46.152
That is the first "F"
I'll ever get.

17:46.195 --> 17:47.979
And hopefully the last.

17:48.023 --> 17:49.285
An "F"?

17:49.329 --> 17:51.505
No, you're too smart for that.

17:51.548 --> 17:53.159
What happened?

17:53.202 --> 17:55.683
The visual aid for my
presentation tomorrow

17:55.726 --> 18:00.079
about Pearl Harbor
got destroyed, so... fail.

18:01.384 --> 18:04.474
Well, maybe I have something
you could use.

18:04.518 --> 18:06.259
I was there, after all.

18:06.302 --> 18:08.609
You were?

18:08.652 --> 18:11.177
My husband was stationed
on the island.

18:11.220 --> 18:14.136
Worst day of my life.

18:14.180 --> 18:15.833
I didn't know if I'd survive

18:15.877 --> 18:18.445
or if I'd ever see him again.

18:18.488 --> 18:19.968
That must have been scary.

18:20.011 --> 18:22.013
Oh... it was.

18:22.057 --> 18:25.060
Hard thing, learning you...

18:25.104 --> 18:28.890
your home's not as safe
as you believed.

18:28.933 --> 18:33.155
But getting through it showed me
what I'm made of.

18:33.199 --> 18:34.765
When Freddie went off to fight,

18:34.809 --> 18:36.767
decided I was going to do
my part, too.

18:36.811 --> 18:38.465
Like Rosie the Riveter.

18:38.508 --> 18:42.947
[laughing]:
Or... or Amy the Aviator.

18:42.991 --> 18:45.298
I got my pilot's license
and went to work for

18:45.341 --> 18:47.038
the Air Transport Command,

18:47.082 --> 18:50.085
ferrying planes for the rest
of the war.

18:50.129 --> 18:52.522
I didn't know women flew
for the military back then.

18:52.566 --> 18:55.177
Uh... technically, we didn't.

18:55.221 --> 18:57.919
Eh... it was a different time.

18:57.962 --> 19:00.922
But even though we were
flying the same aircraft

19:00.965 --> 19:03.620
as the boys,
it didn't count the same.

19:03.664 --> 19:05.187
That sucks!

19:05.231 --> 19:07.189
Stinks. Sorry.

19:07.233 --> 19:09.496
No, it sucked.

19:09.539 --> 19:14.065
Lot of consequences to us
being underestimated like that.

19:14.109 --> 19:17.330
But it teaches you, too.

19:17.373 --> 19:19.767
How to stand up for yourself.

19:22.944 --> 19:27.470
Don't ever let anyone tell you
you're worth less than you are.

19:27.514 --> 19:29.255
You understand me?

19:33.259 --> 19:35.870
Will you tell me more about
your time as a pilot?

19:35.913 --> 19:38.264
[chuckling]: Oh, you don't want
to hear my old war stories.

19:38.307 --> 19:42.006
I do! I really do.

19:42.050 --> 19:43.834
[laughs]

19:43.878 --> 19:45.706
Huh.

19:50.232 --> 19:52.408
HANNAH:
Okay, ready.

19:54.758 --> 19:56.325
Better than the stripes?

19:56.369 --> 20:00.329
You plan to try all these on
and have me weigh in?

20:00.373 --> 20:02.157
If this is some long con
to trick me into

20:02.201 --> 20:04.072
textile design classes,
then I...

20:04.115 --> 20:06.292
Don't think I'm gonna have
any more luck talking you

20:06.335 --> 20:07.858
into school than I did

20:07.902 --> 20:09.338
talking you out of
a wallet chain.

20:09.382 --> 20:10.644
Can you just answer
the question--

20:10.687 --> 20:13.516
better or worse
than the stripes?

20:13.560 --> 20:14.822
[sighs]

20:19.087 --> 20:20.349
I don't know.

20:20.393 --> 20:21.698
Come on, rush event starts
in an hour.

20:21.742 --> 20:23.047
I need to make a decision.

20:23.091 --> 20:24.397
SONNY:
Need an escort to Sorority Row?

20:24.440 --> 20:25.615
Wouldn't mind getting
a peek inside

20:25.659 --> 20:27.226
those houses,

20:27.269 --> 20:31.186
do a recon for some
Lambda Lambda Lambda type op.

20:31.230 --> 20:32.492
[Sonny chuckles]

20:32.535 --> 20:34.581
The idea is that I impress
these girls.

20:34.624 --> 20:36.409
Not sure bringing along
a best friend who smells like

20:36.452 --> 20:38.498
he hasn't showered in a week
is gonna help.

20:38.541 --> 20:40.195
Says the girl who helped shovel

20:40.239 --> 20:43.111
plenty of manure on the ranch
three summers straight.

20:45.461 --> 20:47.768
Why you kissing up to
a bunch of pageant queens?

20:47.811 --> 20:51.511
Why were you in a punk band
until half an hour ago?

20:51.554 --> 20:54.862
More ska than punk--
maybe that was the problem.

20:54.905 --> 20:57.517
You wanna know why I'm rushing,
Sonny?

20:57.560 --> 20:59.214
We're on our own,

20:59.258 --> 21:02.217
figuring out who we are
outside of our families.

21:02.261 --> 21:03.740
Hard enough as it is.

21:03.784 --> 21:07.048
Can't blame me for wanting
a place to fit in.

21:11.226 --> 21:14.621
[chuckles]: All right, Coop,
all right, Coop!

21:15.361 --> 21:18.233
Oh, he's human, folks!

21:18.277 --> 21:19.582
[laughs] Hey, you ever play?

21:19.626 --> 21:21.845
-No.
-Come on down here.

21:23.194 --> 21:25.632
I want you to take three
fingers,

21:25.675 --> 21:27.808
lay it down on the felt,
like that, okay?

21:27.851 --> 21:30.027
The pointer and the thumb,
you make a circle.

21:30.071 --> 21:32.682
That's gonna be your guide,
okay?

21:32.726 --> 21:34.336
Want you to hit right
about there,

21:34.380 --> 21:36.207
not too hard, not too soft.

21:39.994 --> 21:42.431
Oh, oh, oh, hey,
that's all right.

21:42.475 --> 21:44.564
A little more practice,
we'll get this.

21:44.607 --> 21:47.262
Spoken like a senior chief.

21:47.306 --> 21:48.959
How long you stateside for, kid?

21:49.003 --> 21:51.614
-Couple weeks.
-Gonna see your mom?

21:51.658 --> 21:53.703
-Uh...
-Hey, hey.

21:53.747 --> 21:55.879
Don't know you know it's bad
luck to bring up a guy's ex

21:55.923 --> 21:58.012
-during his retirement party?
-[laughs]

21:58.055 --> 22:00.928
Never heard that one before,
but you're right.

22:00.971 --> 22:05.106
Forget the past
and focus on the future.

22:07.238 --> 22:09.458
What's your plan?

22:09.502 --> 22:13.332
-Bet you got offers pouring in.
-I don't know, I just,

22:13.375 --> 22:17.292
working for a defense contractor
doesn't light my fuse.

22:17.336 --> 22:19.381
Thinking about writing a book
about my time in.

22:21.557 --> 22:22.863
I even sent a couple of

22:22.906 --> 22:25.126
chapters off to a publisher.

22:25.169 --> 22:27.041
-Yeah?
-Mm-hmm.

22:27.084 --> 22:28.869
Not sure how that's gonna
go over in the community.

22:31.001 --> 22:33.743
Right, well, lucky for you,

22:33.787 --> 22:35.484
there's not a market for
my stories

22:35.528 --> 22:37.921
about teaching you how to
lasso goats in Iraq.

22:37.965 --> 22:40.533
[laughter]

22:40.576 --> 22:43.623
Oh, you could work on the
motivational speaking circuit.

22:43.666 --> 22:47.844
Really, who the hell's gonna pay
a frogman for his advice?

22:47.888 --> 22:50.586
Huh? I mean,
isn't that why we became SEALs,

22:50.630 --> 22:52.458
we didn't want real jobs
or responsibilities?

22:52.501 --> 22:55.243
[laughter]

22:55.286 --> 22:56.766
[sighs]

22:56.810 --> 22:59.334
Something as meaningful as
the Teams

22:59.378 --> 23:01.336
will come to me eventually.

23:01.380 --> 23:03.904
[billiard balls clatter]

23:08.909 --> 23:10.693
Last time I saw you reading
a newspaper,

23:10.737 --> 23:12.042
you were cutting out your
picture

23:12.086 --> 23:13.696
after winning
the city championship.

23:13.740 --> 23:15.872
Beat Mastbaum by three.

23:15.916 --> 23:17.874
I scored two touchdowns,
got a pick,

23:17.918 --> 23:21.008
and took the prettiest girl in
school out for dinner after.

23:21.051 --> 23:22.923
Shoplifting Wawa hoagies

23:22.966 --> 23:25.665
does not qualify as dinner
or taking me out.

23:25.708 --> 23:27.188
Oh, that was you?

23:27.231 --> 23:30.278
[chuckles]

23:30.321 --> 23:32.019
Real estate listings?

23:33.542 --> 23:35.370
Where'd you get
a Philadelphia Inquirer?

23:35.414 --> 23:37.198
Stopped by a newsstand
on the way home.

23:37.241 --> 23:39.635
Did you know a four-bedroom
house on half an acre in Media

23:39.679 --> 23:41.202
costs $175,000?

23:41.245 --> 23:42.986
Can't get a garage in Coronado
for that much.

23:43.030 --> 23:44.510
Sure we can afford that?

23:44.553 --> 23:45.902
If we move back to Philly,

23:45.946 --> 23:47.904
then I'm gonna enroll at Penn--
that's not cheap.

23:47.948 --> 23:52.387
And maybe after I graduate,
I stick around for my MBA.

23:52.431 --> 23:54.345
Land a CFO track somewhere.

23:54.389 --> 23:56.696
Eventually,
I'll make enough money

23:56.739 --> 23:58.872
that I can buy you
an even nicer house.

23:58.915 --> 24:00.395
And the Flyers.

24:00.439 --> 24:01.657
Oh, I get it,
you're making fun of me.

24:01.701 --> 24:03.224
[Alana chuckles]

24:03.267 --> 24:05.966
Come on,
we've played this game before.

24:06.009 --> 24:07.750
Your enlistment's up in
four months.

24:07.794 --> 24:09.796
Last time you had me convinced
that we were moving to Seattle.

24:09.839 --> 24:11.406
This isn't three years ago.

24:11.450 --> 24:12.929
Yeah, and that's why it's Philly

24:12.973 --> 24:14.975
instead of the
Pacific Northwest.

24:15.018 --> 24:17.151
How come your fantasies never
take us anywhere tropical?

24:17.194 --> 24:20.328
Hey, mock me all you want--
come here.

24:20.371 --> 24:22.199
But things have changed.

24:22.243 --> 24:24.680
We were teenagers when I dragged
you out here, we're parents now.

24:24.724 --> 24:28.510
It's up to us to give our baby
girl the best life possible.

24:28.554 --> 24:31.600
Even though she is insubordinate
and refuses to crawl.

24:31.644 --> 24:33.646
[chuckles]: Uh...

24:36.823 --> 24:40.435
I'm not sure how
insubordinate she is anymore.

24:40.479 --> 24:42.002
What?

24:46.136 --> 24:48.356
JASON:
Oh, what?

24:48.399 --> 24:51.185
[Emma cooing on video]

24:51.228 --> 24:53.317
[Alana chuckles]

25:06.592 --> 25:09.203
Everyone clear on the plan?

25:09.246 --> 25:11.379
[sighs]

25:11.422 --> 25:13.903
SONNY:
Trillions of dollars spent
on developing

25:13.947 --> 25:16.906
the most sophisticated weapons
for the War on Terror.

25:16.950 --> 25:19.561
And there's nothing
more valuable than that.

25:19.605 --> 25:21.998
Can I see it before it, uh,

25:22.042 --> 25:23.913
officially becomes a relic?

25:25.262 --> 25:27.221
Whole thing feels wrong.

25:33.053 --> 25:34.533
[sighs]

25:43.063 --> 25:45.108
ASH:
Okay, I want you to hit
that white ball

25:45.152 --> 25:47.154
right through the one ball.

25:47.197 --> 25:50.897
And remember,
slow is smooth, smooth is fast.

25:54.988 --> 25:56.467
-Excellent.
-Dang it.

25:56.511 --> 25:58.208
-What?
-Didn't get any in.

25:58.252 --> 26:00.210
It's okay, just relax.

26:00.254 --> 26:01.864
Now we need to set up
for your next shot.

26:01.908 --> 26:04.388
-What do you think?
-There isn't one unless

26:04.432 --> 26:06.521
I break those up some more.

26:06.565 --> 26:07.827
I think you might be able

26:07.870 --> 26:09.437
to get that ten ball past
the three ball.

26:09.480 --> 26:11.787
But you're gonna have to hit it
perfectly.

26:13.136 --> 26:14.616
How hard should I hit it?

26:14.660 --> 26:16.662
You tell me.

26:16.705 --> 26:19.926
Hard enough it gets there, not
too hard it gets out of control.

26:21.841 --> 26:24.539
Slow is smooth and smooth
is fast.

26:28.978 --> 26:31.241
-[cheers]
-Holy crap!

26:31.285 --> 26:32.852
-I did it!
-[laughs] My son's a legend!

26:32.895 --> 26:36.682
Just like his old man!
[laughs]

26:42.122 --> 26:45.778
You think maybe
your job's over now,

26:45.821 --> 26:49.608
that I could stay longer than
a week?

26:49.651 --> 26:51.218
Would you like to do that, son?

26:53.481 --> 26:57.006
Like, maybe I could live
with you?

27:03.230 --> 27:04.797
I'd really like that a lot.

27:07.582 --> 27:09.018
What a champ.

27:09.062 --> 27:10.977
Here you go.

27:11.020 --> 27:13.066
♪

27:15.155 --> 27:17.070
Aha!

27:19.159 --> 27:21.204
[laughter]

27:21.248 --> 27:23.642
[sighs]
Still not sure why

27:23.685 --> 27:25.861
you're passing up Topper Harley,
and your favorite munchies,

27:25.905 --> 27:27.994
for the Barbie Brigade.

27:28.037 --> 27:29.648
Probably because you just
described

27:29.691 --> 27:32.302
every night of senior year.
[laughs]

27:32.346 --> 27:33.956
Those were great times.

27:34.000 --> 27:36.959
They were, but we're not in
high school anymore.

27:37.003 --> 27:40.180
Doesn't mean you have to become
a completely different person.

27:40.223 --> 27:43.836
-Stop it.
-Stop what?

27:43.879 --> 27:46.708
Dragging me down for trying
to broaden my horizons.

27:46.752 --> 27:50.712
So kissing up to sorority girls
is broadening horizons?

27:50.756 --> 27:52.322
Beats sitting on the couch

27:52.366 --> 27:54.020
and watching the same movie
over and over again.

27:54.063 --> 27:56.805
I don't even know who you
are anymore.

27:58.459 --> 28:01.375
No, Sonny, you don't know who
you are, and that's the problem.

28:04.421 --> 28:05.858
What's that supposed to mean?

28:05.901 --> 28:08.817
It means that college
is a fresh start for me.

28:08.861 --> 28:11.341
And fine if you don't want to
try it, but you can't

28:11.385 --> 28:14.257
bring your chaos in here
if it's gonna hold me back.

28:14.301 --> 28:15.955
I'm holding you back?

28:19.436 --> 28:21.351
I know you hate change,

28:21.395 --> 28:23.527
but that's what this time
in our life is supposed to be.

28:23.571 --> 28:27.314
You can fight it,
but I don't want to.

28:31.274 --> 28:33.755
I gotta go.

28:50.424 --> 28:52.948
[engine revving,
siren wailing on TV]

28:56.256 --> 28:58.084
Bye.

29:07.702 --> 29:09.486
You know...

29:11.706 --> 29:14.491
...my father hit me.

29:17.277 --> 29:19.322
Is that a threat?

29:22.804 --> 29:24.414
Only thing I learned from it

29:24.458 --> 29:26.721
was that you can't beat
sense into someone.

29:26.765 --> 29:29.724
Figured I could teach by
my example instead of his.

29:29.768 --> 29:30.943
Did you hate him?

29:30.986 --> 29:32.596
Sometimes.

29:35.295 --> 29:36.383
You hate me?

29:40.430 --> 29:41.736
No.

29:43.869 --> 29:45.871
Still feel like I've failed.

29:45.914 --> 29:49.135
Waiting for you to grow up.

29:49.178 --> 29:51.093
Dedicated my life
to helping people,

29:51.137 --> 29:53.617
and can't make a dent
with my own son.

29:53.661 --> 29:57.360
Today was damn near
my worst nightmare.

29:57.404 --> 30:00.146
Just glad it was the precinct
and not the morgue.

30:04.237 --> 30:05.891
Sorry.

30:09.372 --> 30:12.506
I'm done being angry, Ray.

30:14.900 --> 30:16.205
I'm disappointed.

30:16.249 --> 30:18.599
I'm disappointed in you.

30:22.298 --> 30:24.823
Disappointed in myself.

30:30.132 --> 30:31.742
I gotta get to work.

30:33.483 --> 30:36.878
At least help your mother clean
up the kitchen, please.

30:36.922 --> 30:38.880
♪

30:50.674 --> 30:51.893
It's not the same.

30:51.937 --> 30:53.112
What isn't?

30:53.155 --> 30:55.070
Thinking about Philly.

30:55.114 --> 30:57.507
I was just having some fun.

30:57.551 --> 30:59.509
I missed Emma starting to crawl
today,

30:59.553 --> 31:00.859
Alana.

31:00.902 --> 31:02.904
Am I supposed to miss her
first steps, too?

31:02.948 --> 31:04.514
And for what, seeing if I know

31:04.558 --> 31:05.864
how to grab a pair
of bolt cutters when asked?

31:05.907 --> 31:08.344
You love your job.

31:08.388 --> 31:11.913
I do, but I joined to help
the greater good,

31:11.957 --> 31:15.351
but now I'm not so sure what's
more important than this family.

31:15.395 --> 31:18.920
It's getting harder to choose
to put us second all the time.

31:22.576 --> 31:24.056
You really are serious.

31:31.411 --> 31:34.414
You know, I wasn't joking
this morning.

31:34.457 --> 31:36.416
I do want another kid.

31:36.459 --> 31:38.461
Kids.

31:39.810 --> 31:42.596
Well, that explains
the four-bedroom house.

31:43.771 --> 31:46.469
You have a plan for how we
pay the mortgage?

31:46.513 --> 31:47.862
I mean, I'd like to find
something

31:47.906 --> 31:49.342
where I can actually have
an impact,

31:49.385 --> 31:51.344
rather than just practice
for it.

31:51.387 --> 31:53.346
Maybe FBI or...

31:53.389 --> 31:54.825
field medic training was
pretty cool,

31:54.869 --> 31:56.305
maybe get EMT certification.

31:56.349 --> 31:59.308
-Okay.
-I know you have goals, too.

31:59.352 --> 32:00.701
I mean, you gave up
a lot for me.

32:00.744 --> 32:02.529
You want to go to school,

32:02.572 --> 32:04.574
our folks are close enough to
help with double diaper duty.

32:04.618 --> 32:07.012
Well, I always thought
I'd enjoy law school.

32:07.055 --> 32:09.014
Yeah, the way you argue,
you're a natural.

32:10.667 --> 32:13.540
Hey, becoming a SEAL
was my dream job.

32:13.583 --> 32:15.020
Now it's time you find yours.

32:16.630 --> 32:18.545
Well, that does sound nice.

32:18.588 --> 32:22.418
You home more,
and living closer to family.

32:22.462 --> 32:26.118
-Wanna hear the best part?
-Always.

32:26.161 --> 32:29.643
I have two months'
paid leave saved up.

32:29.686 --> 32:32.951
We could be settled in
by Thanksgiving.

32:34.865 --> 32:36.084
I'll call Personnel Support
first thing tomorrow

32:36.128 --> 32:39.044
-and get the ball rolling.
-Yeah.

32:39.958 --> 32:43.352
-And...
-And what?

32:43.396 --> 32:45.572
May as well get started on
a sibling for Emma.

32:45.615 --> 32:47.226
[chuckling]

32:56.452 --> 32:58.367
MRS. HILL:
Good morning, everyone.

32:58.411 --> 33:01.196
Which of our three presenters
would like to go first?

33:03.503 --> 33:06.854
Lisa, the floor is yours.

33:16.603 --> 33:17.996
STUDENT:
What's that?

33:18.039 --> 33:19.736
[others murmuring]

33:19.780 --> 33:21.390
STUDENT 2:
That's tight.

33:21.434 --> 33:26.613
From 1942 through 1944, over
a thousand women flew planes

33:26.656 --> 33:29.877
in the U.S. Army Air Forces
during World War II.

33:29.920 --> 33:32.532
But it wasn't
until the late 1970s

33:32.575 --> 33:34.316
that they were recognized
as part of the military.

33:34.360 --> 33:38.320
My research project seeks
to answer the questions:

33:38.364 --> 33:42.542
what is the history of the
Women's Airforce Service Pilots?

33:42.585 --> 33:44.065
And how did the denial

33:44.109 --> 33:46.502
-of military status affect...
-MRS. HILL: What?

33:46.546 --> 33:50.593
-Wait...
-[students whispering]

33:50.637 --> 33:51.942
No.

33:55.642 --> 33:57.557
Ready, Dad?

33:57.600 --> 33:59.254
ANCHORWOMAN: Information
continues to come in...

33:59.298 --> 34:00.864
What movie's that?

34:02.257 --> 34:04.564
We can now confirm two planes

34:04.607 --> 34:07.871
flew into the Twin Towers
of the World Trade Center

34:07.915 --> 34:11.875
some 20 minutes apart this
morning.

34:11.919 --> 34:15.662
We've gotten reports some
passengers on those planes

34:15.705 --> 34:17.359
may have called loved ones

34:17.403 --> 34:21.233
on the ground to report
they'd been hijacked.

34:21.276 --> 34:23.365
We are still awaiting
confirmation

34:23.409 --> 34:25.367
of flight numbers,

34:25.411 --> 34:27.152
but both planes may have been

34:27.195 --> 34:30.546
in route to Los Angeles
from Boston.

34:30.590 --> 34:33.158
The fire department
and Port Authority

34:33.201 --> 34:35.508
have ordered evacuation
of the World Trade Center...

34:35.551 --> 34:37.510
It's not a movie.

34:37.553 --> 34:38.859
Something bad has happened.

34:38.902 --> 34:41.731
ANCHORWOMAN:
...images of what appears to be

34:41.775 --> 34:45.344
people either falling
or jumping from...

34:45.387 --> 34:47.041
Listen, son.

34:47.085 --> 34:49.391
We're not going fishing.

34:49.435 --> 34:51.437
I have to drive to D.C.

34:51.480 --> 34:54.222
to be on the news
as a military expert.

34:57.138 --> 34:59.749
♪

34:59.793 --> 35:01.577
Are we at war?

35:01.621 --> 35:06.147
No, not yet.

35:06.191 --> 35:08.410
Am I going with you to D.C.?

35:12.762 --> 35:15.374
I called your grandparents,
they're on their way to get you.

35:15.417 --> 35:18.028
I'm sorry, kiddo.

35:18.072 --> 35:20.248
Our plans are on hold for now.

35:20.292 --> 35:23.077
ANCHORWOMAN:
President Bush plans
to address the nation...

35:23.121 --> 35:25.601
♪

35:45.795 --> 35:47.319
[pounding on door]

35:47.362 --> 35:50.322
WOMAN:
We're under attack, wake up!

35:50.365 --> 35:51.497
SONNY:
The hell's going on out there?

35:51.540 --> 35:52.889
WOMAN:
Wake up, it's on TV!

35:52.933 --> 35:54.848
We're being attacked.

35:54.891 --> 35:58.199
GEORGE W. BUSH: Today
we've had a national tragedy.

35:58.243 --> 36:03.509
Two airplanes have crashed
into the World Trade Center

36:03.552 --> 36:06.686
in an apparent terrorist attack
on our country.

36:06.729 --> 36:08.775
And I've ordered that
the full resources

36:08.818 --> 36:11.952
-of the federal government...
-Oh, Sonny...

36:11.995 --> 36:13.649
It's okay.

36:13.693 --> 36:15.173
-...to hunt down...
-It's not.

36:15.216 --> 36:19.916
...and to find those folks
who committed this act.

36:23.920 --> 36:26.227
HANNAH:
Look at it.

36:28.490 --> 36:29.970
It will be.

36:32.102 --> 36:34.801
ANCHORMAN:
Given the coordination
and choice of targets,

36:34.844 --> 36:37.630
certainly, there can be no
question now

36:37.673 --> 36:41.329
that this is a deliberate
and highly coordinated attack.

36:41.373 --> 36:43.984
CORRESPONDENT:
It does appear that way, Jim.

36:44.027 --> 36:46.160
When you think of what
individuals or groups

36:46.204 --> 36:49.859
would want to attack the United
States and have the resources

36:49.903 --> 36:52.862
to plan and achieve
something of this scale...

36:52.906 --> 36:55.038
Agency's gotta be all over this.

36:55.082 --> 36:58.041
Won't be long before they have
a target.

36:58.085 --> 36:59.521
Targets.

36:59.565 --> 37:02.220
CORRESPONDENT:
And-- Oh.

37:03.743 --> 37:06.224
-Teams are gonna get the call.
-[jet engines roaring]

37:06.267 --> 37:08.530
CORRESPONDENT:
Oh, my goodness.

37:08.574 --> 37:11.185
Oh, my goodness...

37:13.796 --> 37:16.103
[people screaming]

37:16.146 --> 37:18.453
-[sirens wailing]
-[panicked chatter]

37:25.068 --> 37:26.722
[coughing]

37:36.558 --> 37:38.691
[people shouting]

37:40.954 --> 37:42.303
Whoa, whoa, nobody below Canal,

37:42.347 --> 37:43.826
-you gotta turn around.
-But my dad's down there!

37:43.870 --> 37:45.654
He's a firefighter,
I have to find him!

37:45.698 --> 37:47.308
I can't let you through, son,
I'm sorry.

37:47.352 --> 37:51.617
He's down there somewhere.
I have to find him, please!

37:51.660 --> 37:54.272
♪

38:12.986 --> 38:15.336
♪

38:19.906 --> 38:22.648
Ain't that something?

38:27.914 --> 38:31.570
Odds were against it,
but it found a way to thrive.

38:37.097 --> 38:42.015
Amid all that darkness, it found
its way toward sunlight.

38:42.058 --> 38:44.191
Resilient.

38:44.234 --> 38:46.411
I can't believe it's been
20 years.

38:46.454 --> 38:48.238
[Sonny exhales]

39:08.302 --> 39:12.175
SONNY:
Day made us all grow up, whether
or not we were ready to.

39:12.219 --> 39:14.613
Can't even imagine what it was
like for an actual kid.

39:16.876 --> 39:19.661
That day changed everything.

39:19.705 --> 39:22.795
Shaped me and the choices
I've made since.

39:25.667 --> 39:28.235
Two days later I walked into
a recruiting office.

39:28.278 --> 39:29.976
And I might've never met
you guys

39:30.019 --> 39:31.978
if it wasn't for that day.

39:37.723 --> 39:39.768
♪

39:48.560 --> 39:50.431
He'd be proud of you.

39:53.826 --> 39:56.742
Be prouder if I hadn't spun out

39:56.785 --> 39:59.005
for two more years before
I enlisted.

40:00.485 --> 40:02.748
You grieved how you grieved.

40:02.791 --> 40:05.403
At the end of the day, you are
where you're meant to be, Ray.

40:07.230 --> 40:09.189
[voice breaking]:
I just, I just wish he knew

40:09.232 --> 40:12.148
how much he helped me become
the man I am today.

40:18.067 --> 40:19.852
[sniffles]

40:19.895 --> 40:22.376
You haven't put that in yet?

40:22.420 --> 40:24.160
Place of honor awaits for
the bolt cutters

40:24.204 --> 40:25.727
from the Abbottabad raid.

40:27.729 --> 40:30.079
Reason the brass sent us here.

40:31.254 --> 40:33.866
I, uh...

40:33.909 --> 40:38.044
I think the victims of the guy
responsible for all this,

40:38.087 --> 40:40.176
it'd be okay memorializing
a piece of the op

40:40.220 --> 40:42.135
that brought him justice.

40:51.318 --> 40:54.364
JASON: The only people that we
should honor and remember today

40:54.408 --> 40:57.542
are the ones that we lost
20 years ago.

40:57.585 --> 41:00.893
♪

